\begin_layout Paragraph*
Conditional CAPM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E[R_{it}|I_{t-1}]=\gamma_{0t-1}+\gamma_{1t-1}\beta_{it-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{it-1}=Cov(R_{it},R_{m}|I_{t-1})/Var(R_{m}|I_{t-1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take unconditional expectation of both sides of equation, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E[R_{it}]=\gamma_{0}+\gamma_{1}\overline{\beta}_{i}+Cov(\gamma_{1t-1},\beta_{it-1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Intuitions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the covariance between the conditional beta of asset i and the conditional
 market premium is zero, then the static CAPM is restored
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
However, in general, the conditional market risk premium and conditional
 beta are correlated
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decompose the conditional beta 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{it-1}$
\end_inset

 into three parts: 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{it-1}=\overline{\beta}_{i}+\upsilon_{i}(\gamma_{1t-1}-\gamma_{1})+\eta_{it-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first part is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\beta}_{i}$
\end_inset

, expected beta
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon_{i}(\gamma_{1t-1}-\gamma_{1})$
\end_inset

: random variable that perfectly correlated with market risk premium.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
beta-prem sensitivity
\emph default
, measured the sensitivity of conditional beta to the market risk premium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{it-1}$
\end_inset

: on average zero and uncorrelated with market risk premium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replace this decomposition into the unconditional expectation equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E[R_{it}]=\gamma_{0}+\gamma_{1}\overline{\beta}_{i}+Var(\gamma_{1t-1})\upsilon_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Implications:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
First, cross-sectionally, the unconditional expected return on any asset
 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 is a linear function of its expected beta and its beta-prem sensitivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The beta-prem sensitivity of an asset measures the instability of the asset's
 beta over the business cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stocks with higher expected betas have higher unconditional expected returns.
 Likewise, stocks with betas that are prone to vary with the market risk
 premium and hence are less stable over the business cycle also have higher
 unconditional expected returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Hence, the one-factor conditional CAPM leads to a 
\series bold
\emph on
two-factor model
\series default
\emph default
 for unconditional expected returns.
\end_layout

