\begin_layout Subsection
The intuitions of the model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The speculative beta model in this paper stands in three main pillars:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Incomplete market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Aggregate disagreement in the market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Short sale constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main idea of this paper is when there are short sale constraints, the
 market is left with only optimistic investors because persimistic investors
 withdraw from the market.
 As a result, the market price is overpriced because the price is from optimisti
c investors.
 This idea is originated from Miller (1977).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hong and Srael (2016) expands this idea by finding that the high beta stocks
 are more sensitive to aggregate disagreement.
 In other words, beta amplifies the disagreement about the macroeconomy.
 Thus, the 
\emph on
high beta stocks tend to be more overpriced
\emph default
 when there is a short sale constraint and high aggregate disagreement,
 relative to the low beta stocks.
 Arbitragers cound not drive the price to intrinsic value due to restricted
 shorting.
 The price in the market is equilibrium overpricing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I do not present the whole model here due to its complication.
 A further reading to paper in detail is more appropriate.
 The following subsection provides brief summary and main findings of two
 predictions of the papers:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
High aggregate disagreement leads to concave (inverted-U shaped) SML (SML
 is relation between stock returns and beta).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
High aggregate disagreement leads to flatter SML.
\end_layout

